      <!-- FAQ -->
      <h2 id="faq" class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold font-heading text-navy mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="space-y-3 mb-10">
        <details class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 shadow-sm group">
          <summary class="px-6 py-4 cursor-pointer font-semibold text-navy hover:text-gold transition-colors list-none flex justify-between items-center">
            <span>What is a decanter centrifuge used for?</span>
            <span class="text-gold group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform">&#9662;</span>
          </summary>
          <div class="px-6 pb-4 text-text-light">
            <p>A decanter centrifuge is used for continuously separating solids from liquids in industrial processes. Common applications include crude oil tank bottom recovery, oilfield drilling mud processing, waste oil de-sludging, industrial and municipal wastewater treatment, fish meal stick-water processing, WVO (waste vegetable oil) de-sludging, rendering plant sludge thickening, and food industry waste streams. Decanters can continuously separate over 50% (v/v) solids from liquids and produce up to 4,000 g&apos;s of centrifugal force.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
        <details class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 shadow-sm group">
          <summary class="px-6 py-4 cursor-pointer font-semibold text-navy hover:text-gold transition-colors list-none flex justify-between items-center">
            <span>How does a decanter centrifuge work?</span>
            <span class="text-gold group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform">&#9662;</span>
          </summary>
          <div class="px-6 pb-4 text-text-light">
            <p>A decanter centrifuge works by exerting high centrifugal force (upwards of 3,000 g) on a slurry of solids and liquids. The slurry enters through an axial feed tube and is accelerated into the rotating bowl, forming a pond. Heavier solids settle against the bowl wall and are conveyed out by a scroll (auger) rotating at a differential speed. The clarified liquid flows over weir plates and exits from the opposite end. The entire process is continuous, allowing large volumes to be processed without interruption.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
        <details class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 shadow-sm group">
          <summary class="px-6 py-4 cursor-pointer font-semibold text-navy hover:text-gold transition-colors list-none flex justify-between items-center">
            <span>What is the difference between a 2-phase and 3-phase decanter centrifuge?</span>
            <span class="text-gold group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform">&#9662;</span>
          </summary>
          <div class="px-6 pb-4 text-text-light">
            <p>A 2-phase decanter separates solids from a single liquid phase &mdash; it produces one solid output and one liquid output. Most de-sludging duties use a two-phase design, including industrial sludge thickening and municipal wastewater. A 3-phase decanter (also called a tricanter) separates solids from two immiscible liquids simultaneously &mdash; for example, separating crude oil from water and sludge, or olive oil from water and biomass, in a single pass.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
        <details class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 shadow-sm group">
          <summary class="px-6 py-4 cursor-pointer font-semibold text-navy hover:text-gold transition-colors list-none flex justify-between items-center">
            <span>How much does a decanter centrifuge cost?</span>
            <span class="text-gold group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform">&#9662;</span>
          </summary>
          <div class="px-6 pb-4 text-text-light">
            <p>A new decanter centrifuge from a quality, established manufacturer starts from around $50,000 for a small capacity unit to over $1 million for a large capacity machine. Remanufactured models typically cost 40% to 60% of comparable new models. Additional accessories such as explosion-proof upgrades, control systems, and pumps add to the cost. Consult Dolphin Centrifuge for competitive pricing on remanufactured Alfa Laval decanters.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
        <details class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 shadow-sm group">
          <summary class="px-6 py-4 cursor-pointer font-semibold text-navy hover:text-gold transition-colors list-none flex justify-between items-center">
            <span>What factors affect decanter centrifuge performance?</span>
            <span class="text-gold group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform">&#9662;</span>
          </summary>
          <div class="px-6 pb-4 text-text-light">
            <p>Key factors affecting decanter centrifuge performance include bowl speed (RPM/centrifugal force), auger or conveyor differential speed, pond depth (controlled by weir plates), beach angle of the conical bowl section, and conveyor pitch. Each of these parameters can be adjusted to optimize separation for specific applications. Read our detailed guide on <a href="/decanter-centrifuge-optimization/" class="text-navy font-semibold hover:text-gold transition-colors">decanter performance optimization</a> for more information.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
        <details class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 shadow-sm group">
          <summary class="px-6 py-4 cursor-pointer font-semibold text-navy hover:text-gold transition-colors list-none flex justify-between items-center">
            <span>What should I consider when buying a remanufactured decanter centrifuge?</span>
            <span class="text-gold group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform">&#9662;</span>
          </summary>
          <div class="px-6 pb-4 text-text-light">
            <p>Important considerations include the manufacturer of the original centrifuge, credentials and experience of the re-manufacturer, the machine&apos;s previous use, wear status of the bowl and conveyor, quality of parts used in the rebuild (especially bearings), balancing of major rotating components, and vibration check and complete testing per OEM specifications. Dolphin Centrifuge adheres to all of these criteria in our remanufacturing process.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>

      <!-- New vs Remanufactured -->
      <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-6 shadow-sm mb-8">
        <h2 id="new-versus-remanufactured" class="text-xl font-bold text-navy mb-3">New versus Remanufactured</h2>
        <p class="text-text-light mb-4">New machines from branded manufacturers like Alfa Laval is the first choice. However, given the cost of new models, buyers often seek remanufactured decanters from trusted and established companies.</p>
        <h3 id="important-considerations" class="font-semibold text-navy mb-2">Important considerations before buying a remanufactured decanter centrifuge</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-1 text-text-light list-disc list-inside ml-2 mb-4">
          <li>Manufacturer of the original centrifuge.</li>
          <li>Credentials &amp; experience of the re-manufacturer.</li>
          <li>Previous use.</li>
          <li>Wear status of the bowl and conveyor.</li>
          <li>Parts used in the rebuild &mdash; especially bearings.</li>
          <li>Balancing of major rotating components.</li>
